doc.after: Common ravens can thrive in varied climates; indeed this species has the largest range of any member of the genus,[45][46] and one of the largest of any passerine.[47] They range throughout the Holarctic from Arctic and temperate habitats in North America and Eurasia to the deserts of North Africa, and to islands in the Pacific Ocean. In the British Isles, they are more common in Scotland, Wales, northern England and the west of Ireland.[38] In Tibet, they have been recorded at altitudes up to 5,000Â m (16,400Â ft), and as high as 6,350Â m (20,600Â ft) on Mount Everest.[46][48] The population sometimes known as the Punjab ravenâdescribed as Corvus corax laurencei (also spelt lawrencii or laurencii) by Allan Octavian Hume but more often considered synonymous with subcorax[17]âis restricted to the Sindh district of Pakistan and adjoining regions of northwestern India.[39][49] Except in Arctic habitats,[50] they are generally resident within their range for the whole year. Young birds may disperse locally.[51]
